  payAmount,                           // 1,000 USDC
  leverage: 10_000n,                   // 1x leverage (no leverage on the $1,000)
  limitPrice,                          // Triggers when BTC <= $58,000
  allowedSlippageBps: 100,             // 1% slippage tolerance
  skipSimulation: true,
});

console.log("Limit order submitted:", tx);
```

## Order Summary

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| **Market** | BTC/USD (Arbitrum) |
| **Direction** | Long |
| **Order Type** | Limit (triggers when BTC ≤ $58,000) |
| **Collateral** | 1,000 USDC |
| **Leverage** | 1x → ~$1,000 position size |
| **Trigger Price** | $58,000 |
| **Slippage** | 1% |

## How It Works

- This creates a **LimitIncrease** order (OrderType 3)
- For a **long limit**, the order executes when the oracle price **drops to or below $58,000**
- The keeper monitors the oracle price and executes automatically when triggered
- If BTC never reaches $58,000, the order remains pending until you cancel it
- You can cancel it anytime with `sdk.orders.cancelOrders([orderKey])`

> **Note:** Adjust `leverage` if you want a leveraged position — e.g., `50_000n` for 5x would give a ~$5,000 position size from $1,000 collateral. Also verify the BTC index token symbol on Arbitrum — it may be `"WBTC"` or `"BTC"` depending on the market configuration; always check `tokensData` at runtime.

